Doublons

# Fonction pour vÃ©rifier les doublons
duplicated2 <- function(x) {
    if (sum(dup <- duplicated(x)) == 0)
        return(dup)
    if (class(x) %in% c("data.frame", "matrix"))
        duplicated(rbind(x[dup, ], x))[-(1:sum(dup))] else duplicated(c(x[dup], x))[-(1:sum(dup))]
}

table(duplicated2(HC_2017$Employee_ID))

Diagramme circulaire

count.data <- data.frame(class = c("Is Manager", "Is not Manager"), n = c(33, 105),
    prop = c(24, 76))

# Add the position of the label
count.data <- count.data %>%
    arrange(desc(class)) %>%
    mutate(lab.ypos = cumsum(prop) - 0.5 * prop)  # add label at the center of the threshold

# Creating pie chart
ggplot(count.data, aes(x = "", y = prop, fill = class)) + geom_bar(width = 1, stat = "identity",
    color = "white") + coord_polar("y", start = 0) + geom_text(aes(y = lab.ypos,
    label = paste(class, "\n", prop, "%")), color = "white") + theme_void() + ggtitle("Manager distribution") +
    theme(legend.position = "none")

table <- round(prop.table(table(data$Is_Manager)) * 100, 0)
lbls = paste(names(table), "\n", table, "%", sep = "")
pie(table, labels = lbls, main = "Manager distribution")

Analyse bivariÃ©e

Barplot format horizontal %

# Fonction pour transformer les Ã©tiquettes en %
f <- function(x) {
    res <- scales::percent(x, accuracy = 1)
    res[x < 0.05] <- scales::percent(x[x < 0.05], accuracy = 1, suffix = "")
    res[x < 0.01] <- ""
    res
}

# Avec ggplot
ggplot(donneesCurrent) + aes(x = HFM_Region, fill = Is_Manager, by = factor(HFM_Region),
    label = f(after_stat(prop))) + geom_bar(position = "fill") + geom_text(stat = "prop",
    position = position_fill(0.5), colour = "white", fontface = "bold", size = 3.5) +
    scale_x_discrete(labels = scales::label_wrap(20)) + scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0,
    0)) + labs(x = "", y = "") + theme_minimal() + theme(legend.position = "right",
    legend.title = element_blank(), panel.grid = element_blank(), axis.text.x = element_blank(),
    axis.text.y = element_text()) + coord_flip()

Table

library(GGally)
ggtable(data = data, columnsX = "HFM_Region", columnsY = c("Gender", "Age_Group"),
    fill = "std.resid", legend = 1) + labs(fill = "ChiÂ²\nResiduals")

The color stands for Chi^2 residuals:

  • red: under represented => smaller numbers than expected under the assumption of independence
  • blue: over represented => bigger numbers than expected under the assumption of independence
  • white: close to the expected numbers under the assumption of independence

Statistiques

Tests de normalitÃ©

The standard deviations (sd) represent less than 50% of the means, which demonstrates low intra-group variations and confirms the absence of outliers.

The means are equal to the medians, which is an indication of symmetry, as are the skew coefficients close to 0.

The negative kurtosis coefficients suggest that the distributions are somewhat compressed, but nevertheless within the normal tolerance interval [-2 ; +2]. 

library(psych)
by(LEBI_HC$Age, LEBI_HC$HFM_Region, psych::describe)

Pour ne retenir que la pvalue

pSW <- function(x) {
    p <- shapiro.test(x)$p.value
    return(p)
}
apply(iris[, 1:4], 2, pSW)
